    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nUnexpected behavior when calling `:totable()` followed by `:next()`, when `:next()` returns multiple values.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```lua\nit = vim.iter({ 1 }):map(function() return 0, 1 end)\nit:totable()\na, b = it:next()\nprint(vim.inspect(a))  -- { 0, 1 }\nprint(vim.inspect(b))  -- nil\n\nit = vim.iter({ 1 }):map(function() return 0, 1 end)\na, b = it:next()\nprint(vim.inspect(a))  -- 0\nprint(vim.inspect(b))  -- 1\n\na, b = it:next()\nprint(vim.inspect(a))  -- nil\nprint(vim.inspect(b))  -- nil\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n```lua\nit = vim.iter({ 1 }):map(function() return 0, 1 end)\nit:totable()\na, b = it:next()\nprint(vim.inspect(a))  -- 0\nprint(vim.inspect(b))  -- 1\n```\nOr `nil, nil` if `:totable()` is meant to exhaust the iterator.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.12.2\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArch Linux, Linux 7.0.3-zen1-2-zen\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nalacritty 0.17.0\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nalacritty\n\n### Installation\n\nArch extra Repository",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "If you repeat the example with `vim.iter(ipairs({ 1 }))` instead of `vim.iter({ 1 })`, you get `nil, nil`: `totable()` exhausts the iterator, so a subsequent `next()` returns `nil`.\n\nFrom reading, seems IterArray:totable() returns the backing table directly to avoid* allocations and copying. Given this, I almost think we shouldn't even expose `next()` on `IterArray` because callers will conflate the meaning of `next` on the iter and on the table. \n\nThis could maybe just become `len + 1` https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/master/runtime/lua/vim/iter.lua#L516. Not sure how breaking this would be though.",
